ce:section.ce:para:
The complete XPS profiles of the HPEI-IBAm0.65 and CDs-2 (
                           Figure S1
                        ) exhibit three peaks attributable to the C 1s, N 1s, and O 1s. The elemental compositions of C, N, and O of HPEI-IBAm0.65 is 72.27%, 18.87%, and 8.85%, respectively. After hydrothermal transformation, the C, N, and O percentages in the CDs-2 sample fluctuate slightly. Three types of carbon atoms can be observed in the C 1s XPS of HPEI-IBAm0.65 and CDs-2, that is, sp2 of CC bond with the binding energy at 284.6 eV, C = O bond at 287.1 eV, and C-N bond at 285.5 eV [35]. Notably, the appearance of the CO bond at 287.1 eV in both HPEI-IBAm0.65 and CDs-2 sample not only suggest the successfully grafting of –CONH- ligand but also demonstrate the stable existence of this bond during CDs formation [36]. N 1s XPS show two peaks at 398.7 eV and 399.4 eV attributed to the graphite-like N and OC-N, respectively, and two peaks located at 532.6 eV and 531.5 eV are observed in O1s XPS, arising from the C-O-C/C-OH and N-CO groups [37,38], respectively. Therefore, combined with the FTIR result, it can be concluded that the amide groups are successfully grafted on the structure of the HPEI molecule and exhibit good stability during the formation process of carbon dots.
